      "message": "Yup, it was a valid point (performance) 3 years ago. Since that time all STL implementations made sure streams are good. In the latest gcc library std::cout is even faster than default printf()\nAnd regarding the utility. I started as a C developer, and I still find the \u003c\u003c overload to be much more readable than %!@#foobar style of the printf. It\u0027s just a matter of preference, nothing more.\n\nAnyway, I changed my code to use StringFormat - mainly because of our own String class, to have one less memory allocation.\n\nP.S. Why every single project keeps writing its own string class? The standard one after C++11 is very decent and is good for most uses (but gaming apps probably)",
